<DOC><DOCNO> AP880617-0131 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 1156EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a PM-HeatWave     06-17 0348</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Heat Wave,0356</SECOND><HEAD>Heat Wave Chilled By Cold Front</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A cold front accompanied by rain and storms that knocked outpower has ended a heat wave across the Northeast after three daysof record highs in the 90s, with today's highs forecast 15 to 20degrees lower.   In Massachusetts, medical officials said 20 deaths in SuffolkCounty since Sunday, 14 of them Thursday, may have been caused inpart by the heat.   The front slid across the upper East Coast during the night andthe clash of cool, dry air with the humid blanket of hot airtouched off storms, some violent.   The Baltimore area was hit by hail and heavy rain that knockedout power to about 22,000 customers. Power was restored to all but300 customers by today.   In northern Massachusetts, the heat wave was broken by strongthunderstorms which brought half-inch hail and wind gusts up to 50mph to Methuen. Three people were reported struck by lightning inthe Merrimack Valley and one was listed in critical condition today.   As of 10 a.m. today, the temperature in Boston had reached only70 degrees, according to the National Weather Service, compared toThursday's high of 92 degrees at Logan International Airport.   About 10,000 Massachusetts Electric Co. customers in Methuen,Lawrence and Dracut were without power for up to five hoursThursday night, utility spokesman Ken Larson said   The cold front gave the Chicago area relief from 90-degree heaton Wednesday, dropping Thursday's high to 82, but temperatures wereexpected to rise back into the 90s on Sunday, said Jim Vermoch, aweather service meteorologist.   The cooling trend brought Chicago no relief from the drought.The area is in its 24th day without rain, added to an alreadyabnormally dry spring, and is about 6 inches short of the normal14{ inches of rain it usually gets by this time of year, he said.   And farther west, a new round of heat was building on thePlains, with thermometers expected to go as high as 103 today inwestern South Dakota.</TEXT></DOC>